{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01MSWYXof4zcCi8qGPro3Wax","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01AKPwGMHAZ7PvqujhZYoA6v","name":"Task","input":{"description":"Write core chapters outline","subagent_type":"markdown-writer","team_name":"category-theory-book","name":"core-writer","prompt":"You are a specialist mathematical writer on a team producing a graduate-level category theory textbook content plan. Your job is to write the detailed chapter outlines for the FOUNDATIONAL chapters of the book.\n\nWrite your output to the file: /Users/darrell/git/teaparty/category_theory_core_chapters.md\n\nCover these chapters in full detail:\n\n1. **Chapter 0 (or Preface/Appendix): Prerequisites and Mathematical Maturity**\n   - What background is assumed (algebra, topology, logic)\n   - How to read the book\n   - Notation conventions\n\n2. **Chapter 1: Categories**\n   - Definition and axioms of a category\n   - Key examples (Set, Grp, Top, Vect_k, Pos, a preorder as a category, a monoid as a category, the discrete category, the indiscrete category, slice and coslice categories, comma categories, arrow category, opposite category)\n   - Special morphisms: monomorphisms, epimorphisms, isomorphisms, retractions, sections, split monos/epis\n   - Theorems: uniqueness of identity, uniqueness of inverses, composition of monos is mono, etc.\n   - Initial and terminal objects, zero objects\n   - Products and coproducts (brief intro, to be expanded in limits chapter)\n   - Subcategories (full, faithful, wide)\n   - Groupoids\n   - Ordering rationale: First chapter, requires only mathematical maturity\n   - Key worked examples: Set in depth, a group as a one-object groupoid, FinSet, matrix categories (linear maps), the fundamental groupoid of a space\n\n3. **Chapter 2: Functors**\n   - Definition of a functor (covariant and contravariant)\n   - The functor category [C, D] / D^C\n   - Concrete functors: forgetful functors, free functors, powerset functor, hom-functors (covariant and contravariant: hom(A,-) and hom(-,B)), product functors, diagonal functor\n   - Faithful, full, essentially surjective functors; fully faithful functors\n   - Equivalences of categories (definition via natural isomorphism of functors and essentially surjective + fully faithful characterization)\n   - The category Cat\n   - Representable functors, the Yoneda lemma (statement and proof), Yoneda embedding\n   - Presheaves (as functors C^op → Set)\n   - Theorems: Yoneda lemma in full, characterization of equivalence of categories\n   - Ordering rationale: Requires Chapter 1\n   - Key worked examples: Fundamental group functor π₁: Top* → Grp, homology functors, free-forgetful adjunction preview (to motivate adjoints), Yoneda embedding for posets and monoids\n\n4. **Chapter 3: Natural Transformations**\n   - Definition of natural transformation\n   - Natural isomorphisms\n   - Vertical and horizontal composition (interchange law)\n   - The functor category [C, D] as a 2-categorical structure\n   - Modification / 2-cells (brief intro to 2-categories)\n   - Whiskering\n   - Theorems: interchange law proof, naturality of hom\n   - Key examples: Determinant as a natural transformation (det: GL_n → k*), double dual embedding for vector spaces, components of adjunctions, unit and counit as natural transformations, natural transformations between presheaves\n   - Ordering rationale: Requires Chapters 1 and 2\n\n5. **Chapter 4: Adjoints (Adjoint Functors)**\n   - Multiple equivalent definitions: unit-counit, hom-set bijection, universal arrow characterization\n   - Proof of equivalence of definitions\n   - Examples: free-forgetful (Grp, Vect, Mod), product-diagonal-coproduct, direct/inverse image sheaves, geometrical realization vs. singular simplicial set, Stone-Čech compactification, tensor-hom adjunction (Currying)\n   - Properties: adjoints preserve limits/colimits (left adjoints preserve colimits, right adjoints preserve limits — RAPL)\n   - Uniqueness of adjoints up to natural isomorphism\n   - The triangle identities (zig-zag identities)\n   - Reflective subcategories\n   - Adjoint lifting theorems (brief mention)\n   - Theorems: RAPL theorem (right adjoints preserve limits), uniqueness of adjoints, adjunctions compose\n   - Ordering rationale: Requires Chapters 1–3\n   - Key worked examples: Tensor-hom adjunction in full detail, free group functor, abelianization functor, compactification, Galois connection as adjunction between posets\n\nFor each chapter, format your output as:\n\n## Chapter N: [Title]\n\n### Prerequisites\n[What chapters/concepts must precede this]\n\n### Core Topics\n[Detailed bullet list of all topics]\n\n### Key Theorems\n[Named theorems with brief statement]\n\n### Key Examples (Worked in Depth)\n[List with rationale for inclusion]\n\n### Suggested Ordering Rationale\n[Why this chapter sits here in the sequence]\n\nBe extremely specific. Name theorems, constructions, and examples precisely. This is for a rigorous graduate-level reference text, comparable in depth to Mac Lane's \"Categories for the Working Mathematician\" or Riehl's \"Category Theory in Context\". Mathematical precision is paramount.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":587,"cache_read_input_tokens":23218,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":587},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0748f996-c1ba-4243-9622-0bd6dfd1400e","uuid":"fb553898-7464-471e-8e10-360df3092c65"}
