{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01EnyLBh5WxVKovM8PADKBxh","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Spawned successfully.\nagent_id: advanced-writer@category-theory-book\nname: advanced-writer\nteam_name: category-theory-book\nThe agent is now running and will receive instructions via mailbox."}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0748f996-c1ba-4243-9622-0bd6dfd1400e","uuid":"5b21ae98-3a72-4db2-9015-2556e1276bf7","tool_use_result":{"status":"teammate_spawned","prompt":"You are a specialist mathematical writer on a team producing a graduate-level category theory textbook content plan. Your job is to write the detailed chapter outlines for the ADVANCED and OPTIONAL chapters of the book.\n\nWrite your output to the file: /Users/darrell/git/teaparty/category_theory_advanced_chapters.md\n\nCover these chapters in full detail:\n\n5. **Chapter 5: Limits and Colimits**\n   - Diagrams as functors J → C (small categories J as index shapes)\n   - Cones and cocones, limit and colimit as universal cones\n   - Products, coproducts, equalizers, coequalizers, pullbacks, pushouts, terminal/initial as special limits/colimits\n   - Completeness and cocompleteness\n   - Construction of all limits from products and equalizers\n   - Filtered colimits and finitely presentable objects\n   - Interchange of limits (commutativity of limits)\n   - The limit-colimit coincidence theorem (in Ab, Set)\n   - Theorems: Limit construction theorem, RAPL (right adjoints preserve limits), special adjoint functor theorem (statement), completeness/cocompleteness via density, theorem on interchange of limits\n   - Ordering rationale: Requires Chapters 1–4 (adjoints used to establish preservation results)\n   - Key examples: Fiber products in algebraic geometry (pullbacks), inverse limits (profinite completions), direct limits in algebra, colimits of diagrams of spaces (pushouts in topology = gluing), sheafification as a colimit\n\n6. **Chapter 6: Monads**\n   - Definition of a monad (T, η, μ) via unit and multiplication\n   - Algebras over a monad (Eilenberg-Moore algebras), EM category\n   - The Kleisli category\n   - Every adjunction generates a monad; monadicity\n   - Monadic functors, Beck's monadicity theorem (precise statement and proof sketch)\n   - Free algebras and adjunctions from monads\n   - Distributive laws\n   - Examples: list monad, powerset monad, state monad, continuation monad, free algebra monads, algebras of the free group monad = groups\n   - Theorems: Beck's monadicity theorem, EM-Kleisli comparison functors, monad from adjunction uniqueness\n   - Ordering rationale: Requires Chapters 1–5\n   - Key examples: List monad on Set, Maybe monad, algebras over the free monoid monad = monoids, double dualization monad on Vect, ultrafilter monad, Beck's theorem applied to ring modules\n\n7. **Chapter 7: Kan Extensions**\n   - Definition (left and right Kan extensions) via universal properties\n   - Pointwise Kan extensions (via limits/colimits)\n   - Kan extensions via coends and ends (introduce coend calculus)\n   - Every functor has a Kan extension along the Yoneda embedding (density)\n   - Global left/right Kan extensions as adjoints to precomposition\n   - Theorems: Existence of pointwise Kan extensions, Kan extension along Yoneda = Yoneda density theorem, uniqueness of Kan extensions\n   - Ordering rationale: Requires all previous chapters — the \"culmination\" of basic category theory\n   - Key examples: Derived functors as Kan extensions, restriction/induction of group representations, sheafification as a Kan extension, left Kan extension = nerve/realization adjunction\n\n8. **Chapter 8: Monoidal Categories**\n   - Definition: monoidal category (C, ⊗, I, α, λ, ρ), coherence axioms\n   - Mac Lane's coherence theorem (statement and proof sketch)\n   - Symmetric, braided, cartesian, cocartesian monoidal categories\n   - Closed monoidal categories (internal hom)\n   - Monoidal functors (lax, oplax, strong), monoidal natural transformations\n   - Monoids and comonoids in a monoidal category\n   - String diagrams (graphical calculus)\n   - Compact closed categories, dualizable objects, traces\n   - Theorems: Mac Lane coherence theorem, Eckmann-Hilton argument\n   - Ordering rationale: Requires Chapters 1–3 (natural transformations); 4–5 helpful for internal hom\n   - Key examples: (Ab, ⊗_Z, Z), (Vect, ⊗_k, k), (Set, ×, 1) and (Set, ⊔, ∅), functor categories with Day convolution, Rel as compact closed, tangles category\n\n9. **Chapter 9: Enriched Categories**\n   - Definition of V-enriched category for V a monoidal category\n   - V-functors and V-natural transformations\n   - The base change of enrichment\n   - Enriched hom-functors and tensors/cotensors\n   - Ordinary categories as Set-enriched categories, Ab-enriched = preadditive, Cat-enriched = 2-category\n   - Enriched limits and colimits (weighted limits/colimits)\n   - Enriched Yoneda lemma\n   - Theorems: Enriched Yoneda lemma, change of base for enrichment\n   - Ordering rationale: Requires Chapters 1–5, 8 (monoidal categories)\n   - Key examples: Ab-enriched categories and additive functors, DG-categories (chain complex enriched), Metric spaces as [0,∞]-enriched categories (Lawvere metric spaces), 2-categories as Cat-enriched categories\n\n10. **Chapter 10: Abelian Categories**\n    - Preadditive and additive categories\n    - Kernels, cokernels, images, coimages\n    - Exact sequences, short exact sequences\n    - Definition of abelian category\n    - The snake lemma, five lemma, nine lemma (proofs)\n    - Projective and injective objects; enough projectives/injectives\n    - The Freyd-Mitchell embedding theorem (statement)\n    - Derived functors (Ext, Tor) via projective/injective resolutions\n    - Exact functors (left exact, right exact)\n    - Theorems: Freyd-Mitchell embedding theorem, snake lemma, five lemma, long exact sequence in homology, existence of enough injectives in module categories\n    - Ordering rationale: Requires Chapters 1–5, 9 (enriched)\n    - Key examples: R-Mod, sheaves of abelian groups on a topological space, chain complexes, coherent sheaves on an algebraic variety\n\n11. **Chapter 11: Topos Theory**\n    - Definition of an elementary topos\n    - Subobject classifier (Ω)\n    - Power objects\n    - The internal language of a topos (Mitchell-Bénabou language, brief)\n    - Grothendieck toposes: sites, Grothendieck topologies, sheaves on a site\n    - Geometric morphisms\n    - Classifying toposes\n    - Connections to logic (intuitionistic logic internal to a topos)\n    - Theorems: Giraud's theorem characterizing Grothendieck toposes, fundamental theorem of topos theory (slice topos), subobject classifier construction\n    - Ordering rationale: Requires Chapters 1–8 (limits, adjoints, monoidal for internal hom)\n    - Key examples: Set as a topos, presheaf toposes (Set^{C^op}), sheaves on a topological space, étale topos, effective topos, Lawvere-Tierney topologies\n\n12. **Appendix A: 2-Categories and Bicategories**\n    - Strict 2-categories (definition, examples)\n    - Bicategories (weakened associativity/unit)\n    - 2-functors, pseudofunctors\n    - Mates correspondence\n    - The Grothendieck construction\n    - Brief mention of (∞,1)-categories and model categories as orientation toward higher category theory\n    - Theorems: Coherence for bicategories (Mac Lane–Paré), mates correspondence\n\nFor each chapter, format your output as:\n\n## Chapter N: [Title]\n\n### Prerequisites\n[What chapters/concepts must precede this]\n\n### Core Topics\n[Detailed bullet list of all topics]\n\n### Key Theorems\n[Named theorems with brief statement]\n\n### Key Examples (Worked in Depth)\n[List with rationale for inclusion]\n\n### Suggested Ordering Rationale\n[Why this chapter sits here in the sequence]\n\nBe extremely specific. Name theorems, constructions, and examples precisely. This is for a rigorous graduate-level reference text, comparable in depth to Mac Lane's \"Categories for the Working Mathematician\" or Riehl's \"Category Theory in Context\". Mathematical precision is paramount.\n","teammate_id":"advanced-writer@category-theory-book","agent_id":"advanced-writer@category-theory-book","agent_type":"markdown-writer","model":"sonnet","name":"advanced-writer","color":"green","tmux_session_name":"in-process","tmux_window_name":"in-process","tmux_pane_id":"in-process","team_name":"category-theory-book","is_splitpane":false,"plan_mode_required":false}}
